{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648391"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:54:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:54:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18313"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18313"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0,0.84,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11031"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65143"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7440"},{"type":"tags","id":"7441"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25602"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures serves as the attachment site for the medial collateral ligament of the knee?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral femoral epicondyle","Intercondylar eminence of the tibia","Tibial tuberosity","Medial femoral epicondyle","Patellar surface of the femur"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe knee joint is a complex hinge joint that involves the articulation of the femur, tibia, and patella. Several ligaments and tendons attach to specific bony landmarks around the knee to provide stability and facilitate movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial femoral epicondyle\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer as it serves as the attachment site for the medial collateral ligament of the knee. The MCL resists forces that push the knee inward, preventing excessive widening of the medial joint space and helps stabilize the knee during activities that involve twisting, cutting, or side-to-side movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral femoral epicondyle\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the attachment site for the lateral collateral ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibial tuberosity\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the attachment site for the patellar ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatellar surface of the femur\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the area where the patella articulates with the femur\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntercondylar eminence of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - This is located between the tibial condyles and serves as an attachment for the cruciate ligaments\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The medial femoral epicondyle is a bony prominence on the distal end of the femur.","The medial femoral epicondyle serves as an attachment site for the medial collateral ligament.","The medial femoral epicondyle is located on the inner side of the knee joint."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65143"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18313"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65143"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T08:06:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T08:07:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11031"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79847"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},